wikipedia_page.main: George Hanbury Field (1 March 1834 – 24 July 1901) was an English cricketer. He played five first-class matches between 1856 and 1859.

The son of George Field, he was born at Clapham in April 1835. He was educated at Eton College, before going up to University College, Oxford. Field played first-class cricket for the Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC) against Cambridge University at Fenner's in 1861. Batting twice in the match, he was unbeaten without scoring in the MCC first innings, while in their second innings he was dismissed for 17 runs by Herbert Salter. By profession he was in business in London and was a justice of the peace for Kent.The funeral of the late Mr Barclay Field. J P., of Lees, Otford. Kent and Sussex Courier. 18 November 1892. p. 6 Field died following a stroke and subsequent short illness in November 1892, at his lodge in Otford, Kent.Deaths.
